{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586087"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:25:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:25:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15057"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15057"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.23,0.05,0.27,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7745"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64413"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7745"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15057"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49845"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18911"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18915"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21221"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64413"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHorseshoe kidney is a congenital fusion anomaly where the lower poles of both kidneys are joined by an isthmus of renal or fibrous tissue. (Image) This congenital anomaly has an incidence of 1 per 400-800 live births. Some one-third of these patients will never have any symptoms and for those that do, the problems usually relate to obstruction, stones, or infection. Some malignancies may be associated with horseshoe kidney.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most commonly associated?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple myeloma","Renal adenoma","Renal oncocytoma","Transitional cell carcinoma","Wilms tumour"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHorseshoe kidney is associated with an increased risk of several conditions, particularly \u003Cstrong\u003Etransitional cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cstrong\u003EWilms tumour\u003C/strong\u003E has a slightly increased incidence in horseshoe kidneys, but less so than transitional cell carcinoma. \u003Cstrong\u003ERenal adenomas\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal oncocytomas\u003C/strong\u003E are not particularly associated with this anatomical variant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe increased risk of transitional cell carcinoma is thought to be related to chronic obstruction and urinary stasis that occurs due to the abnormal anatomy and positioning of the collecting system in horseshoe kidneys. This can lead to chronic inflammation and increased risk of malignant transformation of transitional epithelium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple myeloma\u003C/strong\u003E is not associated with horseshoe kidney. It is a haematological malignancy that affects plasma cells and is not related to congenital renal anomalies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal cell carcinomas occur more frequently in horseshoe kidneys than normal kidneys.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Horseshoe kidney is associated with an increased risk of Wilms tumour and transitional cell carcinoma.","The abnormal anatomy of horseshoe kidneys predisposes to urinary stasis and stone formation.","Horseshoe kidneys occur in approximately 1 in 500 people and are more common in men."],"references":["Fazio L, Razvi H, Chin JL. Malignancy in horseshoe kidneys: review and discussion of surgical implications. Can J Urol. 2003 Jun;10(3):1899-904. PMID: 12892577.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49845"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15057"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21220"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21220"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bDHB1DflXAN1XpPdqkJPPbwswDR4Z5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bDHB1DflXAN1XpPdqkJPPbwswDR4Z5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":570,"height":391}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49845"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T15:38:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T15:38:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7745"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64413"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.e